description.narrative:
1. % of Dry Zone households reporting increased freshwater availability during dry periods;

2. Number of climate-resilient agricultural and livestock practices demonstrated and adopted to support adaptation of marginal farmers and landless households;

3.1. % of Dry Zone  households using climate risk information to adjust their livelihood behavior;

3.2. % of Dry Zone  households with access to early warning information on sudden onset of disasters.

comment.narrative:
1. 74% of households in project targeted townships area currently face shortages of fresh water supply for domestic and agricultural use;

2. Agricultural and livestock practices and extension services in the Dry Zone pay only limited attention to climate change risks;

3. Currently climate risk information on sudden onset of disasters is delivered only to those houses with TV/radio and yet the level of interpretation and response is low. The outreach and understanding of information on slow onset of disasters are even lower.

-Rectification works for defective water infrastructures that was constructed/repaired during 2018 and preparation of a detail assessment/verification report;
- Applications for Community Forestry mgt. plans and Community Forestry certificates prepared and submitted as advised by government counterparts;
-Joint survival counting of rehabilitated/reforested areas conducted and additional patching works, including fire protection arrangements completed;
-Exit strategy and sustainability plan prepared, including handover of project assets and activities to govt and beneficiaries;
-Farmers user groups strengthened to manage project assets and activities in the 5 project townships;
-Technical report on effectiveness, successes and challenges of clmiate-resilient post harvest practices finalized;
-Livestock Farmers Groups monitored for sustainability of livestock banking system (500 HH payback for livestock support);
-Weather forecasts and agro-advisories disseminated to farmers through SESAME mobile application and 216 weather forecast bulletins issued to farmers;
-75 Village Disaster Management Plans revised and finalized and village disaster management teams strengthened through capacity building support;
-Project closure requirements, including PPR and Completion/Lessons Learnt report completed;
-Project assets handed over to government counterparts, as per decision of the final PSC meeting.

